"{\n  \"text\": \"Hey everybody. Petrochemical products are wonderful because they break down very slowly. They create decay resistant substances that we can then work with. Our linoleum countertops, our paper products that are extra water resilient. Our our clothing, everything that surrounds everything that we're built of, everything that we do is covered in petrochemicals because they provide a layer of resistance to biological breakdown. This is actually the problem with the petrochemicals in our environment, is that they break down at a much much slower rate than organic matter. And as organic matter is churned and revived and recycled, the petrochemical products just kind of break down to smaller and smaller units because they're not chemically breaking down. They're staying in the environment and accumulating. And this is a huge issue because it's guming up our decay cycle. It's gumming up the process of reinvigorating the carbon that the plants have taken out of the atmosphere. And as we do this, we're going to find that this breakdown that's not occurring is causing all sorts of problems because these petrochemicals, as they do degrade, degrade into lots of cancerous things and they start to corrupt our carbon chains and they start to interfere with basic life. And as they break down, they just become smaller and smaller and broadcast more and more finely. We have to realize that we cannot make our disposable products with petrochemicals. We need to take the PFAS out of the paper products. We need to take the all the different petrochemicals that we're using for say plastic bags and stop doing that because it's accumulating our environment at such a rate that we can't the environment can't keep up, and we're already seeing alarming loss of insects, which is the front line of the decay cycle. And who knows what's going on with the bacteria level, but we can assume it's not good. And eventually we're going to find ourselves in a place where the world isn't breaking down according to its natural processes. This could be huge. This could affect all biocarbon-based life. We need to realize that disposable products need to break down easily, and covering everything with petrochemicals is the problem. This is not just a uh cultural problem, this is a civilizational problem. This is a life problem. We endanger the most basic forms of life doing this, and it's becoming worse and worse because there's such a huge mass of these petrochemicals, and they are breaking down finer and finer and finer and broadcasting more and more thinly throughout the environment. And we've already found out that wherever we look, we're finding microplastics, we're finding this PFAS, we're finding all these petrochemicals that we've used unbroken down in the environment. Have to realize what's going on. Anyway, uh kind of a gloomy video, but it's a gloomy day, so I decided to make one. Anyway, thanks, y'all.\",\n  \"sentences\": [\n    {\n      \"text\": \" Hey everybody.\",\n      \"start\": 0.64,\n      \"end\": 2.0,\n      \"duration\": 1.36,\n      \"confidence\": 0.965,\n      \"tokens\": [\n        {\n          \"text\": \" He\",\n          \"start\": 0.64,\n          \"end\": 0.8,\n          \"duration\": 0.16,\n          \"confidence\": 0.915\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \"y\",\n          \"start\": 0.8,\n          \"end\": 0.96,\n          \"duration\": 0.16,\n          \"confidence\": 0.997\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \" ever\",\n          \"start\": 1.04,\n          \"end\": 1.2,\n          \"duration\": 0.16,\n          \"confidence\": 0.999\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \"yb\",\n          \"start\": 1.2,\n          \"end\": 1.44,\n          \"duration\": 0.24,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \"ody\",\n          \"start\": 1.44,\n          \"end\": 1.68,\n          \"duration\": 0.24,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"